Content:
[link: #table-of-content] This patch release contains two fixes:
’Ù@b705668a482999694d50175a3dd2d58746c828ff2b9d1af40827e22a4c8f3477ÚkTitle: title: Nushell 0.94.2
Path: ]
Content:
[link: #table-of-content] After the last release, external commands on Windows would incorrectly interpret backslashes in their path as escape sequences despite being unquoted, for example:
```Fenced(Borrowed(""))
alias curl = c:\msys64\clangarm64\bin\curl.exe
               â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”¬â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€
                              â•°â”€â”€ unrecognized escape after '\' in string

```
This is now fixed by 
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/13027] #13027
 and externals should work correctly.
’Ù@f6ea743aefecbb5df65408ef7a445e307a17c89199453c74161559118a464f90ÙúTitle: title: Nushell 0.94.2
Path: ]
Content:
[link: #table-of-content] [link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/pull/13028] #13028
 fixes a bug when an unquoted tilde wasn't expanded properly to the home directory when being a subject of globbing.
’Ù@b235c8d08cfb3095cb21e276eb854404ac04e50e86910806e9ca07f9902532b1Ú…Title: title: Nushell 0.94.2
Path: ]
Content:
[link: https://github.com/nushell/nushell/issues/13020] [link: #table-of-content] Currently, we have one more known regression after 0.94.0, where attempting to run a PowerShell script on Windows using 
``.\script.ps1``
 would result in an error instead of opening an editor with the said file or running the script. We are still looking into this one, but it seems more tricky to resolve, so we decided to release at least the above two bugfixes.
The workaround for this problem is to spawn the file with PowerShell manually, such as 
``pwsh -f script.ps1``
 or 
``powershell.exe -f script.ps1``
.
’Ù@4c7b466f3a73cf7deca5e4471054f0e5179cda1ac99c3d86aa873874b0fd12e5ÚŒTitle: title: Nushell 0.94.2
